{"id":"2305.16408","submitter":"Konrad Kitzing","authors":"Adam Czornik, Konrad Kitzing, Stefan Siegmund","title":"The new notion of Bohl dichotomy for nonautonomous difference equations\n  and its relation to exponential dichotomy","comments":null,"journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.DS","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Bohl dichotomy is a notion of hyperbolicity for linear nonautonomous\ndifference equations that is weaker than the classical concept of exponential\ndichotomy. In the class of systems with bounded invertible coefficient matrices\nwhich have bounded inverses, we study the relation between the set\n$\\mathrm{BD}$ of systems with Bohl dichotomy and the set $\\mathrm{ED}$ of\nsystems with exponential dichotomy. It can be easily seen from the definition\nof Bohl dichotomy that $\\mathrm{ED} \\subseteq \\mathrm{BD}$. Using a\ncounterexample we show that the closure of $\\mathrm{ED}$ is not contained in\n$\\mathrm{BD}$. The main result of this paper is the characterization\n$\\operatorname{int}\\mathrm{BD} = \\mathrm{ED}$. The proof uses upper triangular\nnormal forms of systems which are dynamically equivalent and utilizes a\ndiagonal argument to choose subsequences of perturbations each of which is\nconstructed with the Millionshikov Rotation Method. An Appendix describes the\nMillionshikov Rotation Method in the context of nonautonomous difference\nequations as a universal tool.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 25 May 2023 18:19:13 GMT"}],"update_date":"2023-05-29"}
