{"id":"2305.16730","submitter":"Evgeny A. Stepanov","authors":"Evgeny A. Stepanov, Silke Biermann","title":"Orbital-selective N\\'eel transition in the absence of Hund's rule\n  coupling","comments":null,"journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"cond-mat.str-el","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Orbital degrees of freedom amplify the already rich variety of\ncorrelation-driven phenomena in correlated fermion systems. A prominent example\nare orbital-selective Mott phases where orbitals containing localized and\nitinerant carriers coexist. In this work we investigate possibilities to\nrealize an orbital selective transition to the ordered magnetic state. A\nmechanism for such a transition has been proposed recently on the basis of\ndynamical mean-field theory (DMFT) calculations for a two-orbital Hubbard\nmodel. Considering long-range magnetic fluctuations beyond DMFT changes the\norbital selective type of the N\\'eel transition to a conventional one that\noccurs simultaneously for both orbitals as a consequence of Hund's exchange\ncoupling of magnetic fluctuations of different orbitals. Here, we show that in\nthe absence of Hund's coupling a novel mechanism of an orbital selective N\\'eel\ntransition (OSNT) is at work. On the basis of the two-orbital calculations for\na Hubbard model with different bandwidths we show that the proposed OSNT can be\nrealized for an arbitrary value of the electronic interaction. We demonstrate\nthat in the weak coupling regime this transition is governed by a Slater\nmechanism and thus occurs first for the narrow orbital. At strong coupling a\nHeisenberg mechanism of the OSNT is realized, and the transition occurs first\nfor the wide orbital. Remarkably, at intermediate values of the interaction we\nfind a non-trivial regime of the OSNT, where the Slater mechanism leads to a\nN\\'eel transition that occurs first for the wide orbital.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Fri, 26 May 2023 08:33:19 GMT"}],"update_date":"2023-05-29"}
